@kinitro・26 
Hello fellow storbers,

We've decided to move away from building out a distributed storage network.

Why?

* Building out a permissionless distributed storage network is very hard. While we believe our incentive mechanism was quite robust and our core infrastructure was on its way to becoming more solid, commoditizing storage through a subnet presented numerous additional challenges.
* The supply side of the storage market is highly abundant and saturated, and we believe there's very little margin to be carved out from commoditizing this, as it's already *very effectively commoditized* at *extremely low prices*. Our favorite examples of this include [Storj](https://www.storj.io/pricing) and Sia.  Of course, there's also Hippius (SN75), our very own [Filecoin](https://filecoin.io/filecoin.pdf) on Bittensor.

So what's next for Storb?

messages.content: miner code is not ready yet?
Miner code should be ready, the stuff we are working on are vali and backend related

@ray | SN26 
How many tasks should miner perform?
And can I use all metaworld policies or create new policy?
If you create new task, I can't create new policy.
But kinitro-agent-template doesn't transfer the task name to agent.
no. we're considering starting with MT10/MT50. will keep y'all in the loop.
preferably not. unless your inquiry involves mentioning your hotkey and/or uid or a critical exploit please mention it here.
Can I use sawyer policy for those tasks?
Agent can run only given task.
If the task type is not given, the task cannot be performed.
if you use a hardcoded policy your eval won't be approved.
Then, how can I get task type?
@hihi | SN26 is the best person to ask about the agent template
An agent must know the type of task it needs to perform in order to perform the task.
you would need to write a general policy to serve all tasks under a benchmark like MT10 or MT50
the comps will be structured in a way that tells you what benchmarks you will participating in
So agent's inputs are only observation space and action space?
you can have a look at this repo on how its done (https://github.com/rainx0r/metaworld-algorithms/tree/main) I will release an example agent with that so you can have something to go by
Then agent can get next observation?
ofc after agent predict next action.

you'd probably get task descriptions as well which describe what your agent should be doing. here's an example of what this might look like: https://github.com/spmallick/learnopencv/blob/master/smolvla/smolvla_inference.py#L22-L28

```python
dummy_batch = {
    # a single image observation
    "observation.images.top": torch.rand(batch_size, *img_shape, device="cuda"),
    # a single state observation
    "observation.state": torch.rand(batch_size, state_dim, device="cuda"),
    "task": ["stack the blocks"] * batch_size,
}
```

I think end game here down the line should be a fleet of Unitree robots rented out for revenue to clients running the best agent code built by miners. Ridges style incentive. 

https://x.com/Sentdex/status/1970229914071666873
sentdex spitting straight up facts here.

regarding revenue: i don't know about renting out unitree robots specifically, but going down the route of shipping hardware products down the line and, basically, utilizing miners on the subnet as our R&D wing is something we've been thinking more about.

Hardware is difficult, time consuming and requires high capital and operating cost. It may be better if you first go up the benchmarks rankings like Ridges did fast, demonstrate that you can cut the (non-hardware related) costs and time for hardware companies significantly, and partner with them.
I would be really interested to understand the route Kinitro is going to take whether it is going to be a ridges style competition or something new you've come up with.

What other robotics hardware are being released with open software platforms? You definitely don't want to get into manufacturing and hardware design yourself; but buying off the shelf robots is an easy step. Just most robots are vertically integrated between software and hardware so not so many options for open platforms. 
Unitree would benefit from huge humanoid robot hype potential, affordable hardware and an already open source software ecosystem to plug into and build on. Its a much more challenging form factor though and you'd first want to start with simpler robots!

vat construction methods are super cheap but fucking messy
